Every once in awhile, Christian and I get the chance to shoot for a brand that we’ve long admired. For me, @freepeople has always been one of those brands.

Growing up, I would save my lunch allowance to buy a piece of clothing from Free People, slowly creating a small collection; and I’ll never forget right before I moved into my college dorm freshman year, my mom took me to Free People to make my wardrobe a little less Manhattan, and a little more Boulder. Less structured, more free-spirited, which eventually became a part of my inherent style. 

I got to bring a few @fpmovement pieces with me to the Alps and test run their ski collection on the mountain, and I’m so excited to share this series, and these pieces with you.

For the last 3 years, I’ve been frequenting @bathhouse as my sanctuary for self care and resetting. If you go with an intention of grounding and detoxing, you’ll feel the benefits immediately. Here are my bathhouse rituals:

〰️ 4-5 cycles of SAUNA (10 min) | COLD PLUNGE (2-6 min)| BODY TEMP POOL (3-5 min)
〰️ rinse & meditate
〰️ hour long full body massage with focus on my back
〰️ coffee, breakfast, and intention setting

Go early on weekdays to avoid crowds for the optimal experience, and if you’re there for lunch or dinner, order the meatballs and smoked salmon dip!

Added @newyorkpilates back into my routine this week and am loving it — pilates always feels best with my body. After a few months falling out of my workout routine and feeling emotionally and physically blah at the beginning of this year, I slowly started incorporating light movement into my routine to figure out what my body needs now. It has been a journey to get to the relationship I now have with movement, and it will take a lot of readjusting and patience to maintain it, but I’m committed. 

My current movement routine consists of 2-3 days of strength training, paired with 3-4 days of pilates. NYP has become a favorite part as I always look forward to the classes, the teachers, and how I feel after — strong but not depleted of energy. Linking the promo NYP is doing in my stories so you too can be a Pilates girlie with me 🫶🏼

Happy 30th to the love of my life ❤️‍🔥 your 20s were filled with growth, milestones, adventure, and love. 

By simply being who you are, you show people how to always look for the beauty in everything. You remind us that life really can be that simple when you lead with intention. And the way your tender loving heart leads you through life and all of our experiences, reminds us to soften up around the edges to feel everything. 

Today you begin a new decade, and in a few weeks, we’ll begin a new chapter together. I’m forever grateful for the way you love me, the way that you see the world and expose me to your perspective, the way you are always learning and chasing your curiosity, and the way that you’ve helped me to heal and create a family of our own. 

I’m so excited to see where this year and this decade brings you, and I’m going to cut myself off here before I have no material left for wedding day 😂 I love you forever and beyond CKA

September in Italy loading…

Spent the weekend marrying my best friend 🤍

📷: @julieskarrattphotography

The setting | We were keen on having as many of our guests stay on site to allow everyone to fully check in for the weekend. About 40 minutes outside of Siena, Borgo Casabianca was the perfect, what felt like, rural Italian sleep away camp. Spread across 60 acres, there was something for everyone. Each morning Christian and I would peel ourselves out of bed and gaze out the window to see who was mingling at breakfast. Slowly making our way around the property, some friends were still snoozing, some down at the clay courts playing tennis, some plunging into the pool, and others on their third cappuccino. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The only guests on the property other than our vendors and the amazing staff of Casabianca, were our friends and family. It was the most surreal feeling to have the people from our lives together in one place, thousands of miles from home, there to celebrate us.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
📷: @julieskarrattphotography

After an afternoon storm rolled in on Thursday afternoon, we moved our rehearsal dinner inside, which turned out to be the perfect, cozy, intimate dinner party surrounded by our best friends and families. We laughed until our cheekbones hurt, over-indexed on the tears, and felt resounding love as some of our closest family and friends gave toasts and speeches hugged by 16th century walls. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Thank you for capturing every emotion @julieskarrattphotography 🖤

When life gives you tulle…tie it in a knot and call it a top
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
When the skirt that I wore to our rehearsal dinner found me, I knew I needed to wear it but I didn’t know what with. After ordering and trying several tops that didn’t do the skirt justice, @mclindon and I headed to the garment district 4 days before leaving New York as a last attempt at feeling inspired by something to wear with it. I left with 2 yards of tulle mesh, an ivory ribbon, and a vague vision of what I would create after dusting my sewing machine off. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
But as life has it days before leaving to your wedding overseas, the to-do list grew and the sewing machine never got plugged in. An hour before aperitivo would kick off, Camille and I were in my room wrapping the tulle around me in every which way — tucking it here, twisting it there — and finally securing it in a knot. “Ahhh perfecto,” Camille would exclaim. As it turned out, there wasn’t a top better made for the Ralph Lauren skirt other than one created on the fly out of a wad of fabric at the bottom of my suitcase.

📷: @julieskarrattphotography

An end of summer soirée, Slim Arrons Edition. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
We have long been lovers of Slim Aarons -- the lifestyle of the characters that he captures, the destinations, and of course the way that his work makes viewers feel as if they are transported into one of his scenes. When we saw this venue, we knew that Slim Aarons needed to be injected into the weekend in the form of a pool party. We kicked off the weekend and closed out summer the best way we know how: galavanting with spritzes in hand on an estate in the Italian countryside surrounded by our favorite people.

Thank you @julieskarrattphotography for making us the characters in our very own Slim Aarons feature 📷

I've always known that I wanted a September wedding, in part because Christian and I celebrate the month of September as our anniversary, this month being our 10th. Italy in September is (in our opinion) the best time to be here -- the weather when sunny begs for a mid-day dip, but by the time the sun is setting, it cools down enough to layer with a light jacket. There aren't as many people flooding the streets, and the Italian saying "la dolce far niente", takes on a life of its own in the surrender of the last weeks of summer.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Our pool party was our way of sharing this feeling that we feel each year that we return to Italy in September with our guests, and making them the main characters of our own Slim Aarons piece. ⛱️
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

September 1st 2023 〰️ A month ago today we went to the courthouse, and with one witness — our best friend who happens to be Christian’s sister — we made it official. We told only our family and closest friends and we brought Beau to celebrate with us since he wasn’t coming to Italy. Christian wore his late grandfather’s tuxedo jacket, and I wore a custom top by @thelgproject. My bouquet was made of dahlias that we grew together in our Brooklyn garden. We lived in our own little world for a day, just as I dreamed of my courthouse wedding growing up in New York City. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
We didn’t plan anything for the day after the courthouse — after all, we were leaving 5 days later for our “actual” wedding and the to-do list was long. Catherine told us that she made a brunch reservation, and after the courthouse called an Uber that took us to Pier 60. In lieu of a brunch, she had chartered a private boat for us for the afternoon with bagels, lox, and champagne. It was a movie, truly one of the best days of our lives.

📷: @ashleehuff @ashleehuffweddings

Our all white welcome party 〰️ On Friday evening we invited all of our guests to the terrace for a pizza party. I’ve always found a little fun in poking the traditional etiquette of such high-gravity events, and besides that, I’d been wearing white for two years at this point and loved the idea of wearing something not white. So we flipped the switch — we asked our guests to wear all white so that in a (stunning, might I add) crowd of guests in white, we were the something blue.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

They say that your wedding is supposed to be one of the best days of your life. So we made our wedding 3 days long — and some of the best days of our life they were. We laughed, we cried, we barely slept, and all with the most important people beside us. 

The biggest thank you to our incredible videographers @romavera_films who captured all of it and were also the life of the party while doing it. 

WE’RE MARRIED!! 💗 #CiaoAthertons
september sixteenth | a month ago today 🤍

I didn’t sleep more than four hours the night before, and when I did wake up on wedding morning, it was misty outside, as Tuscany often is at dusk with dew covering the grass and the pea gravel stone tie-dyed with drying water marks. It was chilly as I sat on the swings and thought about the 10 years of our relationship that got us here.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
My biggest priority on wedding day was to feel like myself. To write and journal while drinking a cappuccino, the way I do most mornings at home. To ground myself and feel present. As someone who has daily playdates with anxiety, I knew that wedding day could be a superbowl for my anxiety if I didn’t go into it with intention. And familiarity with routines.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The nerves were on extended release all day, but as my best friends and our moms came in and out of our bridal suite, I felt the most calming presence. To be surrounded by the most important women in my life while writing love notes to them and Christian, scream singing Lizzie McGuire, and being fed caprese. Girl time I’ll cherish forever 💕

📷: @julieskarrattphotography

When your friends just whip this video up at the end of your wedding weekend 😭 @krispyshorts 

My favorite part about watching videos back from the weekend is that through them we get to experience the other little intimate and raw moments again, like my wardrobe malfunction, or as Christian says, “maldrobe” as we walked back down the aisle, the deep breaths, the swarm of bugs, and even the state of the boys room with tables clad in pasta and beer. In some ways it’s comforting knowing that your wedding day is just another day 💘

We laughed, we danced, we cried, and we dined at one long table, all together. It was the greatest dinner party we’ve ever thrown 🕯️
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

Our ceremony was the most grounding, beautiful hour of our lives. We laughed, cried, stumbled on our words, and were led through some of the most sacred moments by my best friend, who also happens to be Christian’s sister. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Catherine honored the people who showed up for us, not only on the day of our wedding but throughout the past 10 years of our relationship. She spoke to the pillars of our relationship, offered advice, and invited three of our friends up to share readings that reminded them of us and that would guide us through the next chapter of our lifelong book. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
My intention for the ceremony was to be fully present. After we asked Catherine to marry us almost a year ago, we wanted the content of it to fully be up to her. Other than a few conversations about our relationship and what we wanted out of the ceremony, we weren’t at all involved in it — it was a surprise to us, and it couldn’t have been more beautiful or felt more like us. It sealed the deal, moved us and everyone there beyond words, and kicked off the celebration to continue the rest of the night.
Stills from the day after we wed, shot by my husband 🎞️
Moments of sweet nothings on our buddymoon 🍝
A little @oldprada never hurt anyone ♠️

One of our favorite things to do together on each holiday is to have no plans for 2 or 3 days — no accommodations booked, no agenda, just a car and a road that will inevitably lead to somewhere beautiful. It forces me to release control, be fully present, and be curious. 

5 days after our wedding when we left our buddymoon in Forte dei Marmi, we did just that. Still in recovery and wanting to stay in our own little world for a few more days, we headed back into the rolling hills of Tuscany and explored every little town that we passed. Arezzo was filled with so much history and art. We spent an entire day just going from restaurant to restaurant to order more wine, more pasta, and people watch from a different vantage point. After all, there is a reason why we continue to end up in Italy, even after our wedding, with no plan and no agenda.

Unposted files from Antibes, one of my favorite memories of 2023. It was the week before our wedding and we secretly flew to the south of France to surprise my best friend for her engagement. For four days we did as the French do before flying to Italy to get hitched 🪨

The happiest year of my life so far. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
My favorite moments (not all photographed) included St. Anton, Austria, one of my best friend’s baby shower weekends, new memories and mundane moments with Christian and Beau, growing our dahlia garden, the hundreds of amazing shoots we did, 3 different work trips to St. Martin, Hotel Mojo, Nantucket, weekends upstate, my best friend’s wedding in Portugal, my bridal shower, eloping at city hall, my best friend’s engagement in France, marrying Christian, turning 30, date nights, learning a new appreciation for my body and health, growing closer with my girlfriends, our friends moving in next door, having all of our friends in Italy for a week, and all of the little moments of doing nothing.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Thank you, 2023, for everything you gave me
